      "description": "### 1.Register User\n\nCreates a new user account in the system.\n\n- **Method:** `POST`\n    \n- **Endpoint:** `/auth/login` _(Note: Review your collection path; typically this is_ `_/auth/register_`_)_.\n    \n- JSON{ \"email\": \"[admin@example.com](https://mailto:admin@example.com)\", \"username\": \"test3\", \"password\": \"password123\"}\n    \n\n### 2\\. User Login\n\nAuthenticates credentials and issues tokens.\n\n- **Method:** `POST`\n    \n- **Endpoint:** `/auth/login`\n    \n- **Description:** Returns **Access** and **Refresh** tokens in both the response body and secure cookies.\n    \n- JSON{ \"email\": \"[test@gmail.com](https://mailto:test@gmail.com)\", \"password\": \"password123\"}\n    \n\n### 3\\. Token Refresh\n\nGenerates a new access token using a valid refresh token by default it uses refresh token cookie but refresh token can be sent in body.\n\n- **Method:** `POST`\n    \n- **Endpoint:** `/auth/refresh`\n    \n\n### 4\\. User Logout\n\nTerminates the user session by clearing the security tokens.\n\n- **Method:** `POST`\n    \n- **Endpoint:** `/auth/logout`\n    \n- **Authentication:** Required (Bearer Token)\n    \n- **Description:** This route invalidates the user's current session. It typically removes the Refresh Token from the database/whitelist and clears the `accessToken` and `refreshToken` cookies from the browser.\n    \n\nEndFragment"
    },
